    &gt; In my class, I have methods A(),B(), C(), where A() must 
    &gt; be called before B(), B() before C(). I have individual 
    &gt; test cases for each method. In order to run the tests in 
    &gt; the specified order, I must arrange the actual methods in 
    &gt; the appropriate order. I know this is not a good thing, 
    &gt; so how do I avoid it? I really hate to lump them into one 
    &gt; testcase. 
    &gt; 
    &gt; Thanks,
    &gt; 
    &gt; 
    &gt; Scott

This could be a place for non-JUnit assertions in your code. [I subscribe to
the Heresy that XP can be enhanced by design-by-contract, using assertions
in addition to unit testing.]

boolean aWasCalled = false;
boolean bWasCalled = false;
boolean cWasCalled = false;

void a()
{
   Assert.isFalse( bWasCalled );
   Assert.isFalse( cWasCalled );
   aWasCalled = true;
   ....
}

void b()
{
   Assert.isTrue( aWasCalled );
   Assert.isFalse( cWasCalled );
   bWasCalled = true;
   ....
}

void c()
{
   Assert.isTrue( aWasCalled );
   Assert.isTrue( bWasCalled );
   ....
}

Now your code communicates that a() must be called before b(), which must be
called before c(). This also tests the unit tests, in that your non-JUnit
Assert class methods should throw an unchecked exception if b() is called
before a(), or c() is called before b() and a().

While people are calling this a &#39;code smell&#39;, does the following smell? 
     a() means &quot;open file&quot;
     b() means &quot;write to file&quot;
 and c() means &quot;close file&quot;.

However, since the three methods apparently work together, they probably
should be tested together.


